Today in History is presented by Freshman History student Anthony Braesch. (teacher- Kim Henry).
"Now, we have inscribed a new memory alongside those others. It’s a memory of tragedy and shock, of loss and mourning. But not only of loss and mourning. It’s also a memory of bravery and self-sacrifice, and the love that lays down its life for a friend–even a friend whose name it never knew."
– President George W. Bush

post_text: The 8th grade science class is learning about Newton's 3 Laws of motion. In order to develop understanding, students constructed enclosed tracks were they crashed their cars and recorded the difference in recoil of four different subject cars. Force and motion differences were then discovered by the greatest recoiled car, this was then recorded and graphed.

shared_text:
Loup City Public Library
May 29 at 3:55 PM ·

We plan to reopen on Tuesday!

There will be a 10 person at a time limit. We will continue doing Story Time online for now as it would be difficult to do social distancing with crafts and reading. We request that you wear masks when coming to the library as I work at a nursing home too and don't want to increase the risk to the people there. Computer usage will be allowed with social distancing restrictions for necessary use. Hand sanitizer will be available. Returned books will continue to be cleansed and quarantined prior to checkout again.

We look forward to seeing all of you again!

Today was our day. The senior's last day of high school. May 8th has been marked on our calendars for a couple months now. No, this is not how we planned on spending our last day but it will be a time to remember for years to come. Today seemed like the best fit to show our appreciation for the Loup City Public Schools Staff. The Class of 2020 would like to thank you for everything. We would not be who we are without your guidance.

shared_text:
University of Nebraska-Lincoln
April 17 at 3:00 PM ·

Today the University of Nebraska announced a new initiative, the Nebraska Promise, to provide hope to Nebraskans who may be struggling.

The Nebraska Promise will provide free undergraduate tuition at the University of Nebraska’s four campuses (UNL, UNK, UNO and UNMC) for students from families at or below the median household income in the state. With COVID-19 throwing many lives into disarray, some high school students may feel that college is not within their reach right now. We're here to say: it is.

President Carter notes the program "won't require any additional funding from the state or mean higher tuition rates for other students. Rather, the university plans to reallocate existing dollars from elsewhere in the NU system."

Read more from Lincoln Journal Star ›› http://ow.ly/3YVr50zhl4j
Learn more about the Nebraska Promise initiative ›› nebraska.edu/nebraska-promise #NUforNE

post_text:
In honor of National Vietnam War Veterans Day LCPS wants to share the Washington DC trip pictures when the students visited the Vietnam Memorial.

National Vietnam War Veterans Day is observed every year on March 29 and is a way to thank and honor our nation’s Vietnam veterans and their families for their service and sacrifice.

November 1, 1955 to May 15, 1975

~Nine million Americans serving during that time
~6.4 million Americans living today
~2.7 million U.S. service members who served in Vietnam
~58,000 whose names are memorialized on a black granite wall in our Nation’s capital
~304,000 who were wounded
~1,253 Missing in Action (MIA) heroes who have not yet returned to American soil
~2,500 Prisoners of War (POWs)

As this is a fluid situation and we promised our patrons to re-evaluate the situation each night we have decided Loup City Public Schools will be closed through March 31st at which time we will re-evaluate our situation. I appreciate your cooperation and understanding as we move through these uncharted waters.

Angela Simpson, Superintendent

post_text:
I have had the opportunity to visit with some of our parents and appreciate the phone calls I have received with questions and hope we can continue to be of help. At this time Loup City Public Schools does not have the conditions necessary to close our schools. But I would be remiss if I didn't ask our families to think about and discuss a plan of action should that become necessary in the future. We continue to work with Sherman County Emergency Management, City of Loup City, Loup Basin Public Health, Educational Service Unit 10, the Department of Education and the State of Nebraska to keep up to date and do the right thing for our students.

We have and will continue to make announcements about any activity changes. To date the following activities have been cancelled: FFA, FBLA, and FCCLA State conferences.

I appreciate all of the communication and hope we at Loup City Public Schools can be helpful in this current situation.

post_text: Happy 100th Day! The Kindergartners celebrated being 100 DAYS SMARTER by doing many 100 activities. They enjoyed doing an experiment with 100 drops of water, building a 100 cup structure, seeing how high they could stack 100 pennies, using 100 cubes to build a structure and made a 100th day snack. We are so excited for the rest of the school year to see how much brighter we can get!

Expect to Win Today! When you walk on the court, on the field, into a meeting or in a classroom... expect to win. Expect success and your positive beliefs often lead to positive actions and outcomes. You win in your mind first and then you win in the hearts and minds of your customers, students or fans.

TODAY'S LUNCH: (Pulled Pork Sandwich, BBQ Chicken Sandwich, or Chef Salad), French Fries, and Salad Bar.
TOMORROW’S BREAKFAST: Waffle.

There are still some students that need to pay for and pick-up their FCCLA T-Shirts from Ms. Hornickel. The cost of the T-shirts are $14. Please get this done by the end of this week.

There are t-shirt order forms in the office for “Breast Cancer Awareness” night which will be on February 11th during the home basketball games. Show your support and order a t-shirt today!

Upcoming activities/events:
- - Today - Basketball at Riverside, (Cedar Rapids). Members need dismissed at 2:35. JV boys and girls will start at 4:30. Varsity Girls will play at 6:00 and Varsity Boys will play at approximately at 7:45.
- - Saturday - Speech Meet at Grand Island, (CNFL #1).
Wrestling at 9:30 at Palmer.

Lunch at 12:13 for grades 7-9
Lunch at 12:43 for grades 10-12

post_text: To show the importance of food safety and sanitation, students in Food & Nutrition class became CSI agents-Culinary Scene Investigators. Students were to “detect” the kitchen and food safety violations in the FCS kitchens. Test your own knowledge, can you find all 20 violations?
